"Tadonléké R.D.","Evidence of warming effects on phytoplankton productivity rates and their dependence on eutrophication status",2010,"Limnology and Oceanography","55","3",,"973","982",,,10.4319/lo.2010.55.3.0973,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955585925&partnerID=40&md5=ba7c1aa7273083faeefbc135ede20e76","Institut National de la Recherche Agronomique, Unité Mixte de Recherche 42, Centre Alpin de Recherche sur les Réseaux Trophiques des Ecosystèmes Lacustres, Thonon-les-Bains, France","Tadonléké, R.D., Institut National de la Recherche Agronomique, Unité Mixte de Recherche 42, Centre Alpin de Recherche sur les Réseaux Trophiques des Ecosystèmes Lacustres, Thonon-les-Bains, France","Using 31-yr data from measurements in a lake that has experienced change in eutrophication status, I showed that the effects of global warming on chlorophyll a (Chl a)-normalized maximum rates of photosynthesis (Pmax : Chl a) may be positive, nonsignificant, or negative, depending on nutrient availability. The magnitude of Pmax : Chl a change in response to warming showed hyperbolic relationships with phosphorus concentrations; it was positive and constant when total phosphorus (TP) in the lake water exceeded 22 μg P L -1 (eutrophic conditions) but was negative when TP was lower (nutrient-poor conditions), indicating direct negative effects of warming on primary productivity (PP) under phosphorus scarcity. Vertically integrated PP responses corroborate those of Pmax : Chl a. These data also showed long-term seasonal variations in the sensitivity of phytoplankton productivity to temperature. The observed hyperbolic curves strongly suggest that the ""limiting-nutrient cell quota""-based mechanism reported so far only in laboratories (by studies analyzing temperature-nutrient effects on microalgal growth or photosynthesis) operates in nature and plays a key role in determining phytoplankton response to warming of waters. The present findings provide insight on how phytoplankton productivity may respond to future warming in lakes of differing eutrophication status. © 2010, by the American Society of Limnology and Oceanography, Inc.",,"chlorophyll a; data interpretation; database; eutrophication; global warming; growth rate; growth response; lacustrine environment; microalga; nutrient availability; phosphorus; photosynthesis; phytoplankton; primary production; seasonal variation; water temperature",,,,,,"(1990) Water Assessment Methods, , ASSOCIATION FRANÇAISE DE NORMALISATION. 4th ed. Association Française de Normalisation; Behrenfeld, M.J., Falkowski, P.G., Photosynthetic rates derived from satellite-based chlorophyll concentration (1997) Limnol. Oceanogr., 42, pp. 1-20; Climate-driven trends in contemporary ocean productivity (2006) Nature, 444, pp. 752-755. , doi:10.1038/nature05317; Blanc, P., Corvi, C., Khim-Heang, S., Rapin, F., (2000) Evolution Physico-chimique du Léman, , http://www.cipel.org, Rapport de la Commission Internationale Pour la Protection des Eaux du Léman, campagne 1999, 33-58; Chrzanowski, T.H., Grover, J.P., Effects of mineral nutrients on the growth of bacterio- And phytoplankton in two southern reservoirs (2001) Limnol. Oceanogr., 46, pp. 1319-1330; Coles, J.F., Jones, R.C., Effect of temperature on photosynthesis-light response and growth of phytoplankton species isolated from a tidal freshwater river (2000) J. Phycol., 36, pp. 7-16. , doi:10.1046/j.1529-8817.2000.98219.x; Davison, R.I., Environmental effects on algal photosynthesis: Temperature (1991) J. Phycol., 27, pp. 2-8. , doi:10.1111/j.00223646.1991.00002.x; Dokulil, M.T., Twenty years of spatially coherent deepwater warming in lakes across Europe related to North Atlantic Oscillation (2006) Limnol. Oceanogr., 51, pp. 2787-2793; Doney, S.C., Plankton in a warmer world (2006) Nature, 444, pp. 695-696. , doi:10.1038/444695a; Elliott, J.A., Jones, I.D., Thackeray, S.J., Testing the sensitivity of phytoplankton communities to changes in water temperatur